        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> The original question didn't state the relative sizes of the guilds, yet most people immediately assumed that Guild A was the smaller of the two guilds. Yet, if both Guilds were of the same size and had spent hours amassing people for Gorenaire, should Guild B really be expected to wait an extra hour before knowing whether they would walk away empty handed? True, most people would've left the moment they saw the dragon was taken and would go do something else rather than wait for the chance that another guild would fail. If both Guilds were at the Gore-killing stage though, then I'd say that Guild B should be right to have a shot at it.</P><P>But then it was revealed that Guild B was much larger and Gore was trivial. Truly, I can't see why they would even bother to wait around to take on Gore, much better things to kill where you didn't have to wait for someone else, unless of course they were trying to get an epic-thingy for someone. So, both Guilds wanted Gore for a reason: Guild A because it would be a milestone, Guild B because of an epic piece (I doubt that anyone would bother to wait and buff up just to flex their muscles at a smaller guild, time is better spent killing something else and screwing another Guild of similar power).</P><P>Logically speaking, Guild A had a shot and failed. Why shouldn't Guild B have a go? Can anyone define a universally respectable number of times to let someone have a go at something before it's time to say "Enough"? No, because some will say "once" and some will say "10 times" and some will say "until they give up". After all, Guild A wanted something, and Guild B also likely wanted something. Who's need should be greater? Neither.</P><P>From a more human point of view however, given that Gore was trivial to Guild B and they could kill it easily, it would've taken them less hassle to get enough people to kill it when it next spawned. Whereas Guild A probably planned for a week to have enough people on to kill it. In which case it would've been nice to let Guild A have another shot. It wouldn't be fair to the person that Guild B was killing Gore for ("Sorry dude, but we can't get your piece today. We have to be nice to other Guilds, after all"), but I guess that Guild B should be able to get something close to epic for that person anyway.</P><P>I don't see it as a question of morals, more as one of "niceness". If Guild B could've gotten something better, then they probably should've let Guild A have another shot. But no real judgement can be made without knowing the motivation behind Guild B's killing of Gore.</P><P>As a note: I estimate that I am in a Guild that is similar sized to Guild A. I've had similar run-ins, and even worse ones (one time we were told to get out of the way when another guild started pulling Tormax to the zone).</P><P>Tenaiya Soulscorcher</font></td>
