        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> I'm not entirely sure why the common perception seems to be that any guilds which are relatively weak and struggling are always to be looked upon as a Noble Band of Honorable Heroes, while guilds which are even fractionally stronger and struggle less with the same mobs / raids are invariably Marauding Gangs of Vicious Jackass Thugs Who Only Live To Step On The Little Guy And Inflate Their Collective Ego.</P><P>Here's a True Story...<BR>starring Guild A as the Brave Valliant Underdogs<BR>also starring Guild B as the Cruel and Heartless Oppressors (I'm a member, so obviously nothing I say can be treated as anything other than malevolent propaganda)<BR>and guest-starring Guild C as the Evil Insidious Overlords</P><P>Guild B was toodling around in Grieg's End one night and was wrapping up when one of the guild's trackers alerted us that Rhag`Zhezum had spawned in the Ssraeahza Temple.  We headed that way (OBVIOUSLY making several stops along the way to commit random acts of cruel inhumanity against hapless innocents) but soon, our guild leader (hereafter referred to as Guildleader B) told us to wait, because Guild A was already set up and had attacked Rhag`Zhezum.  No problem.  We set out in search of other things to do.  But soon we heard that Guild A had wiped out.</P><P>At this point Guildleader B sends a tell to Raidleader A asking him if Guild A plans to try Rhag`Zhezum a second time.  Raidleader A said they were indeed going to try again.  No problem.  Guildleader B asks Raidleader A if Guild A would be OK with Guild B killing Rhag`Zhezum in the event of a second failed attempt by Guild A.  This got no response at all.</P><P>Guildleader B tells Raidleader A that Guild B will wait for 1 hour or 1 more failed attempt, and at that point Guild B would move in, kill Rhag`Zhezum and help Guild A with CR if need be.  This also got no response whatsoever.</P><P>Guildleader B asks another member of Guild B to speak to Raidleader A, as they are long-time friends, and the hope is that Raidleader A will not simply ignore his friend, and issue some sort of reply other than silence.</P><P>Well, lo and behold, the reply that issued forth was, "GET THE F--- AWAY FROM OUR MOB!"  Astute readers will recognize this handy phrase from the best-selling book, "How To Win Friends And Influence People".</P><P>By this time, 30 mins to an hour of tells back and forth between Raidleader A and Guildleader B have gone on, and what to my wondering eyes should appear but Guild C on the horizon, who didn't bother asking Guild A if it was OK with them, and swiftly moved in and killed Rhag`Zhezum.  </P><P>Prior to this, Guild B had a policy of leaving "first come first served" mobs alone when other guild were attempting them, and to simply allow them as many attempts as they wished.  For example, if Velketor the Sorcerer is up, and you want to throw your guild against him 15 times in a row, that would have previously been your prerogative.  No longer.  No, we're not going to train your CR or attempt to KS once you've already engaged.  But we're also not going to wait hours while you become better at Futility!(153) and another less diplomatic guild comes in and gets down to the business of killing a mob we would already have been finished with if we hadn't wasted time getting your permission.</P><P>Moral of the Story:  Attempting new stuff is wonderful.  Hooray for you if you succeed, because that's even better than attempting.  However, don't expect another guild to sit there and cheer you on as you fail for the 26th time.</P><P>Words like "respect" have been tossed about in this thread; I ask this - isn't it rather disrespectful to the people in your OWN guild - the people who have put in their time and effort into the guild, and who are in fact your friends - to tell them that no, we aren't going to kill Mob_00 to get your epic piece or maybe some spells or whatever, because the Valliant Underdogs wants to "practice".</P><P> </font></td>
